message.content:
 To align a row of divs to the right using Flex in CSS, you can use the following example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Flex Align Example</title>
    <style>
      .container {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: flex-end;
      }
      div {
        background-color: #eee;
        width: 50px;
        height: 50px;
        margin: 10px;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <div></div>
      <div></div>
      <div></div>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
```

In this example, the container element has its `display` property set to `flex`, and we use the `justify-content` property with a value of `flex-end` to align the row of divs to the right. Each div has a width and height, along with some margin for spacing. You can replace the div elements with your content, and the alignment will still apply.
